assistantMessage.text:
Certainly! I'd be happy to show you how to apply suggestion #2 and propose some code to use. Here's how we can separate the speed test logic into a service class:

1. Create a new file called `speed_test_service.dart` in your `lib` folder.

2. In `speed_test_service.dart`, implement the following class:

```dart
import 'package:speed_test_dart/classes/classes.dart';
import 'package:speed_test_dart/speed_test_dart.dart';

class SpeedTestService {
  final SpeedTestDart _tester = SpeedTestDart();
  List<Server> _bestServersList = [];

  Future<void> setBestServers() async {
    final settings = await _tester.getSettings();
    final servers = settings.servers;
    _bestServersList = await _tester.getBestServers(servers: servers);
  }

  Future<double> testDownloadSpeed() async {
    return await _tester.testDownloadSpeed(servers: _bestServersList);
  }

  Future<double> testUploadSpeed() async {
    return await _tester.testUploadSpeed(servers: _bestServersList);
  }

  bool get isReadyToTest => _bestServersList.isNotEmpty;
}
```

3. Now, modify your `_SpeedTestWidgetState` class in `sc_speedtest.dart`:

```dart
class _SpeedTestWidgetState extends State<SpeedTestWidget> {
  final SpeedTestService _speedTestService = SpeedTestService();

  double downloadRate = 0;
  double uploadRate = 0;
  double _speedValue = 0;

  bool readyToTest = false;
  bool loadingDownload = false;
  bool loadingUpload = false;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    WidgetsBinding.instance.addPostFrameCallback((_) {
      _initializeSpeedTest();
    });
  }

  Future<void> _initializeSpeedTest() async {
    await _speedTestService.setBestServers();
    setState(() {
      readyToTest = _speedTestService.isReadyToTest;
    });
  }

  Future<void> _testDownloadSpeed() async {
    setState(() {
      loadingDownload = true;
    });
    final _downloadRate = await _speedTestService.testDownloadSpeed();
    setState(() {
      downloadRate = _downloadRate;
      _speedValue = downloadRate;
      loadingDownload = false;
    });
  }

  Future<void> _testUploadSpeed() async {
    setState(() {
      loadingUpload = true;
    });
    final _uploadRate = await _speedTestService.testUploadSpeed();
    setState(() {
      uploadRate = _uploadRate;
      _speedValue = uploadRate;
      loadingUpload = false;
    });
  }

  // ... rest of the class remains the same
}
```

This approach separates the speed test logic into a dedicated service class, improving maintainability and making the widget more focused on UI rendering. The `SpeedTestService` encapsulates all the interactions with the `SpeedTestDart` package, while the widget state manages UI-related properties and methods.

To open the SpeedTestWidget from a button in the middle of the homepage, you can follow these steps:

1. In your homepage file (likely `home.dart` or `homepage.dart`), add a button in the middle of the layout:

```dart
ElevatedButton(
  onPressed: () {
    Navigator.push(
      context,
      MaterialPageRoute(builder: (context) => SpeedTestWidget()),
    );
  },
  child: Text('Speed Test'),
)
```

2. Make sure to import the SpeedTestWidget at the top of your homepage file:

```dart
import 'package:your_project_name/sc_speedtest.dart';
```

3. If your homepage is using a Scaffold, you can add this button to the body, perhaps inside a Center widget for proper alignment:

```dart
Scaffold(
  appBar: AppBar(title: Text('Home')),
  body: Center(
    child: ElevatedButton(
      onPressed: () {
        Navigator.push(
          context,
          MaterialPageRoute(builder: (context) => SpeedTestWidget()),
        );
      },
      child: Text('Speed Test'),
    ),
  ),
