1. Create a new file, for example, `lib/common_app_bar.dart`, to define your custom `AppBar` widget.

2. Inside `lib/common_app_bar.dart`, define a custom `AppBar` widget that encapsulates the common properties and styling you want across your screens. For example:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class CommonAppBar extends StatelessWidget implements PreferredSizeWidget {
  final String title;
  final List<Widget>? actions;

  const CommonAppBar({
    Key? key,
    required this.title,
    this.actions,
  }) : super(key: key);

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return AppBar(
      title: Text(title),
      actions: actions,
      // Add any other common properties or styling here
    );
  }

  @override
  Size get preferredSize => const Size.fromHeight(kToolbarHeight);
}
```

In this example, the `CommonAppBar` widget accepts a `title` parameter to set the title of the `AppBar` and an optional `actions` parameter to specify any additional actions.

3. In your screen widgets, import the `CommonAppBar` widget and use it instead of the default `AppBar`. For example, in `lib/home.dart`:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'common_app_bar.dart';

class HomeScreen extends StatelessWidget {
